Recursion is a method where a function calls itself to solve smaller instances of the same problem, breaking down complex tasks into simpler ones. Think of recursion like Russian nesting dolls—each doll contains a smaller one inside, and you keep opening dolls until you reach the smallest one. For example, consider calculating the factorial of a number n (written as n!). The factorial of 5 (5!) is 5 × 4 × 3 × 2 × 1. Using recursion, you define factorial(n) as n multiplied by factorial(n-1), with the base case factorial(1) = 1 to stop the recursion. In code, it looks like this:

function factorial(n) {
  if (n === 1) return 1;
  else return n * factorial(n - 1);
}

Here, the function calls itself with smaller values until it reaches 1, then multiplies all the returned values back up. This approach elegantly solves problems that naturally break down into similar subproblems.
